  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Resilience Plus: Niger</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">agropastoralists and small holder farmers</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022; The Resilience Plus project is an intensive, multifaceted approach to meeting immediate cash needs and building long-term resiliency.
&#x2022; Cash for Work activities support participants with the resources they need to access food during this emergency crisis.
&#x2022; Access to credit, trainings on improved production, processing and marketing, and entrepreneurial opportunities for women will empower beneficiaries to increase yields and profits, thereby assisting to protect their future food security. The Tripartite Rural Financing Model will connect beneficiaries with local financial institutions to provide necessary capital for purchasing inputs.
&#x2022; Land and water conservation projects, including tree planning and riverbank protection, will reduce production costs, improve yields and protect the environment for future generations of smallholder farmers.

&#x2022; 54,000 participants will increase their cash-assets through Cash for Work activities, recovering 320 hectares of land and rehabilitating 115,000 water conservation structures. The immediate cash will help beneficiaries meet their short-term food security needs in exchange for work on community land and water conservation projects. 
&#x2022; # smallholder producers will gain skills enabling them to better cope with changing climate patterns. Access to credit and trainings on improved production will help increase yields, improve food security and build resiliency to future shocks. 
&#x2022; 200 women will have increased entrepreneurial opportunities through trainings in animal husbandry and business techniques to develop the technical capacity of women to fatten animals for a convertible source of income.</narrative>
  </description>
